[src:ethers-js/api-contract] A Contract object is a meta-class (a class whose definition is defined at runtime), which communicates with a deployed smart contract on the blockchain and provides a simple JavaScript interface to call methods, send transaction, query historic logs and listen for its events.
[src:ethers-js/api-contract] The name for an event used for subscribing to Contract events.
[src:ethers-js/api-contract] The parameters will be dereferenced when passed into the listener.
[src:ethers-js/api-contract] ContractEvent - A filter from the contract.filters, which will pass only the EventPayload as a single parameter, which includes a .signature property that can be used to further filter the event.
[src:ethers-js/api-contract] TopicFilter - A filter defined using the standard Ethereum API which provides the specific topic hash or topic hashes to watch for along with any additional values to filter by.
[src:ethers-js/api-contract] This will only pass a single parameter to the listener, the EventPayload which will include additional details to refine by, such as the event name and signature.
[src:ethers-js/api-contract] DeferredTopicFilter - A filter created by calling a ContractEvent with parameters, which will create a filter for a specific event signature and dereference each parameter when calling the listener.
[src:ethers-js/api-contract] The fallback or receive function if any.
[src:ethers-js/api-contract] All the Events available on this contract.
[src:ethers-js/api-contract] This is generally a Provider or a Signer, which dictates what operations are supported.
[src:ethers-js/api-contract] For example, a Contract connected to a Provider may only execute read-only operations.
[src:ethers-js/api-contract] This can be an address, ENS name or any Addressable, such as another contract.
[src:ethers-js/api-contract] To get the resolved address, use the getAddress method.
