[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] A ContractRunner is a generic interface which defines an object capable of interacting with a Contract on the network.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] The more operations supported, the more utility it is capable of.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] The most common ContractRunners are Providers which enable read-only access and Signers which enable write-access.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] Required for pure, view or static calls to contracts.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] The provider used for necessary state querying operations.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] This can also point to the ContractRunner itself, in the case of an AbstractProvider.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] The interface to an EIP-1193 provider, which is a standard used by most injected providers, which the BrowserProvider accepts and exposes the API of.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] See EIP-1193 for details on this method.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] Provider info provided by the EIP-6963 discovery mechanism.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] An EnsPlugin allows a Network to specify the ENS Registry Contract address and the target network to use when using that contract.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] Various testnets have their own instance of the contract to use, but in general, the mainnet instance supports multi-chain addresses and should be used.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] The chain ID that the ENS contract lives on.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] The Universal Resolver Contract Address.
