[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] This may be useful when managng offline transactions.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] Resets the nonce, causing the NonceManager to reload the current nonce from the blockchain on the next transaction.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] A PreparedTransactionRequest is identical to a TransactionRequest except all the property types are strictly enforced.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] Storage slots included in the access list are warmed by pre-loading them, so their initial cost to fetch is guaranteed, but then each additional access is cheaper.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] When using call or estimateGas, this allows a specific block to be queried.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] Many backends do not support this and when unsupported errors are silently squelched and "latest" is used.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] The chain ID for the network this transaction is valid on.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] A custom object, which can be passed along for network-specific values.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] When using call, this enables CCIP-read, which permits the provider to be redirected to web-based content during execution, which is then further validated by the contract.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] There are potential security implications allowing CCIP-read, as it could be used to expose the IP address or user activity during the fetch to unexpected parties.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] The maximum amount of gas to allow this transaction to consume.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] The gas price to use for legacy transactions or transactions on legacy networks.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] Most of the time the max*FeePerGas is preferred.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] The EIP-1559 maximum total fee to pay per gas.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] The actual value used is protocol enforced to be the block's base fee.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] The EIP-1559 maximum priority fee to pay per gas.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] The nonce of the transaction, used to prevent replay attacks.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] A Provider is the primary method to interact with the read-only content on Ethereum.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] It allows access to details about accounts, blocks and transactions and the ability to query event logs and simulate contract execution.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] Account data includes the balance, transaction count, code and state trie storage.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] Simulating execution can be used to call, estimate gas and get transaction results.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] The broadcastTransaction is the only method which allows updating the blockchain, but it is usually accessed by a Signer, since a private key must be used to sign the transaction before it can be broadcast.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] This is part of the necessary API for executing a contract, as it provides a common property on any ContractRunner that can be used to access the read-only portion of the runner.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] Broadcasts the signedTx to the network, adding it to the memory pool of any node for which the transaction meets the rebroadcast requirements.
[src:ethers-js/api-providers-p01] If the call reverts, it will throw a CallExceptionError which includes the revert data.
