[src:ethers-js/application-binary-interface] An **application binary interface** (**ABI**) is an interface exposed by software that is defined for in-process machine code access.
[src:ethers-js/application-binary-interface] Often, the exposing software is a library, and the consumer is a program.
[src:ethers-js/application-binary-interface] An ABI is at a relatively low level of abstraction.
[src:ethers-js/application-binary-interface] Interface compatibility depends on the target hardware and the software build toolchain.
[src:ethers-js/application-binary-interface] In contrast, an application programming interface (API) defines access in source code, which is a relatively high-level, hardware-independent, and human-readable format.
[src:ethers-js/application-binary-interface] An API defines an interface at the source code level, before compilation, whereas an ABI defines an interface to compiled code.
[src:ethers-js/application-binary-interface] API compatibility is generally the concern for system design and of the toolchain.
[src:ethers-js/application-binary-interface] However, a programmer may have to deal with an ABI directly when writing a program in multiple languages or when using multiple compilers for the same language.
[src:ethers-js/application-binary-interface] A complete ABI enables a program that supports an ABI to run without modification on multiple operating systems that provide the ABI.
[src:ethers-js/application-binary-interface] The target system must provide any required libraries (that implement the ABI), and there may be other prerequisites.
[src:ethers-js/application-binary-interface] ABIs include the Intel Binary Compatibility Standard (iBCS) and the System V Release 4 ABIs for various instruction sets.
[src:ethers-js/application-binary-interface] An **embedded ABI** (**EABI**), used on an embedded operating system, specifies aspects such as file formats, data types, register usage, stack frame organization, and function parameter passing of an embedded software program.
[src:ethers-js/application-binary-interface] Each compiler and assembler that supports an EABI creates object code that is compatible with code generated by other such compilers and assemblers.
[src:ethers-js/application-binary-interface] This allows developers to link libraries generated by one compiler with object code generated by another.
[src:ethers-js/application-binary-interface] Typically, an EABI is optimized for performance for the limited resources of the target embedded system.
[src:ethers-js/application-binary-interface] Therefore, an EABI may omit abstractions between kernel and user space typically found in desktop operating systems.
[src:ethers-js/application-binary-interface] The choice of EABI can affect performance.
[src:ethers-js/application-binary-interface] Widely used EABIs include the PowerPC, Arm, and MIPS EABIs.
[src:ethers-js/application-binary-interface] Specific software implementations like the C library may impose additional limitations to form more concrete ABIs; one example is the GNU OABI and EABI for ARM, both of which are subsets of the ARM EABI.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] This is a very short introduction to Ethers, but covers many of the most common operations that developers require and provides a starting point for those newer to Ethereum.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] If using NPM, you must first install Ethers.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] Everything in Ethers is exported from its root as well as on the ethers object.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] There are also exports in the package.json to facilitate more fine-grained importing.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] Generally this documentation will presume all exports from ethers have been imported in the code examples, but you may import the necessary objects in any way you wish.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] To begin, it is useful to have a basic understanding of the types of objects available and what they are responsible for, at a high level.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] A Provider is a read-only connection to the blockchain, which allows querying the blockchain state, such as account, block or transaction details, querying event logs or evaluating read-only code using call.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] If you are coming from Web3.js, you are used to a Provider offering both read and write access.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] In Ethers, all write operations are further abstracted into another Object, the Signer.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] A Signer wraps all operations that interact with an account.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] An account generally has a private key located somewhere, which can be used to sign a variety of types of payloads.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] To make any state changes to the blockchain, a transaction is required, which requires a fee to be paid, where the fee covers the associated costs with executing the transaction (such as reading the disk and performing maths) and storing the updated information.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] If a transaction reverts, a fee must still be paid, since the validator still had to expend resources to try running the transaction to determine that it reverted and the details of its failure are still be recorded.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] Transactions include sending ether from one user to another, deploying a Contract or executing a state-changing operation against a Contract.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] A Contract is a program that has been deployed to the blockchain, which includes some code and has allocated storage which it can read from and write to.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] It may be read from when it is connected to a Provider or state-changing operations can be called when connected to a Signer.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] Once a Transaction has been submitted to the blockchain, it is placed in the memory pool (mempool) until a validator decides to include it.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] This very first thing needed to begin interacting with the blockchain is connecting to it using a Provider.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] When requesting access to the authenticated methods, such as sending a transaction or even requesting the private key address, MetaMask will show a pop-up to the user asking for permission.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] If you are running your own Ethereum node (e.g.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] Geth) or using a custom third-party service (e.g.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] INFURA), you can use the JsonRpcProvider directly, which communicates using the link-jsonrpc protocol.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] When using your own Ethereum node or a developer-base blockchain, such as Hardhat or Ganache, you can get access to the accounts with JsonRpcProvider-getSigner.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] All units in Ethereum tend to be integer values, since dealing with decimals and floating points can lead to imprecise and non-obvious results when performing mathematic operations.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] As a result, the internal units used (e.g. wei) which are suited for machine-readable purposes and maths are often very large and not easily human-readable.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] For example, imagine dealing with dollars and cents; you would show values like "$2.56".
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] In the blockchain world, we would keep all values as cents, so that would be 256 cents, internally.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] So, when accepting data that a user types, it must be converted from its decimal string representation (e.g.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] "2.56") to its lowest-unit integer representation (e.g.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] And when displaying a value to a user the opposite operation is necessary.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] In Ethereum, one ether is equal to 10 ** 18 wei and one gwei is equal to 10 ** 9 wei, so the values get very large very quickly, so some convenience functions are provided to help convert between representations.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] Once you have a Provider, you have a read-only connection to the data on the blockchain.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] This can be used to query the current account state, fetch historic logs, look up contract code and so on.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] To write to the blockchain you require access to a private key which controls some account.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] In most cases, those private keys are not accessible directly to your code, and instead you make requests via a Signer, which dispatches the request to a service (such as MetaMask) which provides strictly gated access and requires feedback to the user to approve or reject operations.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] A Contract is a meta-class, which means that its definition is derived at run-time, based on the ABI it is passed, which then determined what methods and properties are available on it.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] Since all operations that occur on the blockchain must be encoded as binary data, we need a concise way to define how to convert between common objects (like strings and numbers) and its binary representation, as well as encode the ways to call and interpret the Contract.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] For any method, event or error you wish to use, you must include a Fragment to inform Ethers how it should encode the request and decode the result.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] Any methods or events that are not needed can be safely excluded.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] There are several common formats available to describe an ABI.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] The Solidity compiler usually dumps a JSON representation but when typing an ABI by hand it is often easier (and more readable) to use the human-readable ABI, which is just the Solidity signature.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] A read-only method is one which cannot change the state of the blockchain, but often provide a simple interface to get important data about a Contract.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] When adding event listeners for a named event, the event parameters are destructed for the listener.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] There is always one additional parameter passed to a listener, which is an EventPayload, which includes more information about the event including the filter and a method to remove that listener.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] When querying within a large range of blocks, some backends may be prohibitively slow, may return an error or may truncate the results without any indication.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] This is at the discretion of each backend.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] A private key can do a lot more than just sign a transaction to authorize it.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] It can also be used to sign other forms of data, which are then able to be validated for other purposes.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] For example, signing a message can be used to prove ownership of an account which a website could use to authenticate a user and log them in.
[src:ethers-js/getting-started] Many other more advanced protocols built on top of signed messages are used to allow a private key to authorize other users to transfer their tokens, allowing the transaction fees of the transfer to be paid by someone else.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Node.js allows developers to use JavaScript for writing command line tools and server-side scripting.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Running Javascript on the server is commonly used to generate dynamic web page content before the page is sent to the user's web browser.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Consequently, Node.js represents a "JavaScript everywhere" paradigm, unifying web-application development around a single programming language, as opposed to using different languages for the server- versus client-side programming.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Node.js has an event-driven architecture capable of asynchronous I/O.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] These design choices aim to optimize throughput and scalability in web applications with many input/output operations, as well as for real-time Web applications (e.g., real-time communication programs and browser games).
[src:ethers-js/node-js] The Node.js distributed development project was previously governed by the Node.js Foundation, and has now merged with the JS Foundation to form the OpenJS Foundation.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] OpenJS Foundation is facilitated by the Linux Foundation's Collaborative Projects program.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Node.js was initially written by Ryan Dahl in 2009, about 13 years after the introduction of the first server-side JavaScript environment, Netscape's LiveWire Pro Web.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] The initial release supported only Linux and Mac OS X.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Its development and maintenance was led by Dahl and later sponsored by Joyent.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Dahl demonstrated the project at the inaugural European JSConf on November 8, 2009.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Node.js combined Google's V8 JavaScript engine, an event loop, and a low-level I/O API.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] In January 2010, a package manager was introduced for the Node.js environment called npm.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] The package manager allows programmers to publish and share Node.js packages, along with the accompanying source code, and is designed to simplify the installation, update and uninstallation of packages.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] In June 2011, Microsoft and Joyent implemented a native Windows version of Node.js.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] The first Node.js build supporting Windows was released in July 2011.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] In January 2012, Dahl yielded management of the project to npm creator Isaac Schlueter.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] In January 2014, Schlueter announced that Timothy J.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] In December 2014, Fedor Indutny created io.js, a fork of Node.js created because of dissatisfaction with Joyent's governance as an open-governance alternative with a separate technical committee.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] The goal was to enable a structure that would be more receptive to community input, including the updating of io.js with the latest Google V8 JavaScript engine releases, diverging from Node.js's approach at that time.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] The Node.js Foundation, formed to reconcile Node.js and io.js under a unified banner, was announced in February 2015.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] The merger was realized in September 2015 with Node.js v0.12 and io.js v3.3 combining into Node v4.0.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] This merge brought V8 ES6 features into Node.js and started a long-term support release cycle.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] By 2016, the io.js website recommended returning to Node.js and announced no further io.js releases, effectively ending the fork and solidifying the merger's success.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] In 2019, the JS Foundation and Node.js Foundation merged to form the OpenJS Foundation.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] The Node.js logo features a green hexagon with overlapping bands to represent the cross-platform nature of the runtime.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] The Rocket Turtle was chosen as the official Node.js mascot in February 2024 following a design contest.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Node.js allows the creation of web servers and networking tools using JavaScript and a collection of "modules" that handle various core functionalities.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Modules are provided for file system I/O, networking (DNS, HTTP, TCP, TLS/SSL or UDP), binary data (buffers), cryptography functions, data streams and other core functions.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Node.js's modules use an API designed to reduce the complexity of writing server applications.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Since version 22.6.0, Node.js natively supports both JavaScript and TypeScript, allowing TypeScript files to be executed without a separate compilation step.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] The TypeScript support was contributed by Node.js TSC member Marco Ippolito.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] In addition, many compile-to-JS languages are available, allowing Node.js applications to also be written in CoffeeScript, Dart, ClojureScript, and others.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Node.js is primarily used to build network programs such as web servers.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] The most significant difference between Node.js and PHP is that most functions in PHP block until completion (commands execute only after previous commands finish), while Node.js functions are non-blocking (commands execute concurrently and use callbacks to signal completion or failure).
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Node.js is officially supported by Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows 8.1 and Server 2012 (and later), with Tier 2 support for SmartOS and IBM AIX and experimental support for FreeBSD.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] OpenBSD also works, and LTS versions are available for IBM i (AS/400).
[src:ethers-js/node-js] The source code may also be built on similar operating systems that are not officially supported, such as NonStop OS and Unix servers.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Node.js enables development of fast web servers in JavaScript using event-driven programming.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Developers can create scalable servers without using threading by using a simplified model that uses callbacks to signal the completion of a task.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Node.js connects the ease of a scripting language (JavaScript) with the power of Unix network programming.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Node.js was built on top of Google's V8 JavaScript engine since it was open-sourced under the BSD license, and it contains comprehensive support for fundamental protocols such as HTTP, DNS and TCP.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] JavaScript's existing popularity made Node.js accessible to the web-development community.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] There are thousands of open-source libraries for Node.js, most of which are hosted on the npm website.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Multiple developer conferences and events are held that support the Node.js community, including NodeConf, Node Interactive, and Node Summit, as well as a number of regional events.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] The open-source community has developed web frameworks to accelerate the development of applications.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Such frameworks include Express.js, Socket.IO, Sails.js, Next.js and Meteor.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Various packages have also been created for interfacing with other languages or runtime environments such as Microsoft .NET.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Modern desktop IDEs provide editing and debugging features specifically for Node.js applications.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Such IDEs include Atom, Brackets, JetBrains WebStorm, Microsoft Visual Studio (with Node.js Tools for Visual Studio, or TypeScript with Node definitions), NetBeans, Nodeclipse Enide Studio (Eclipse-based) and Visual Studio Code.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Some online IDEs also support Node.js, such as Codeanywhere, Eclipse Che, Cloud9 IDE and the visual flow editor in Node-RED.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Node.js is supported across a number of cloud-hosting platforms such as Jelastic, Google Cloud Platform, AWS Elastic Beanstalk, Azure Web Apps and Joyent.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] New major releases of Node.js are cut from the GitHub main branch every six months.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Even-numbered versions are cut in April and odd-numbered versions are cut in October.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] When a new odd version is released, the previous even version undergoes transition to Long Term Support (LTS), which gives that version 12 months of active support from the date it is designated LTS.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] After these 12 months expire, an LTS release receives an additional 18 months of maintenance support.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] An active version receives non-breaking backports of changes a few weeks after they land in the current release.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] A maintenance release receives only critical fixes and documentation updates.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] The LTS Working Group manages strategy and policy in collaboration with the Technical Steering Committee of the Node.js Foundation.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Node.js is a JavaScript runtime environment that processes incoming requests in a loop, called the event loop.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Node.js uses libuv under the hood to handle asynchronous events.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Libuv is an abstraction layer for network and file system functionality on both Windows and POSIX-based systems such as Linux, macOS, OSS on NonStop, and Unix.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Node.js relies on nghttp2 for HTTP support.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] As of version 20, Node.js uses the ada library which provides up-to-date WHATWG URL compliance.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] As of version 19.5, Node.js uses the simdutf library for fast Unicode validation and transcoding.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] As of version 21.3, Node.js uses the simdjson library for fast JSON parsing.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Node.js operates on a single-thread event loop, using non-blocking I/O calls, allowing it to support tens of thousands of concurrent connections without incurring the cost of thread context switching.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] The design of sharing a single thread among all the requests that use the observer pattern is intended for building highly concurrent applications, where any function performing I/O must use a callback.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] To accommodate the single-threaded event loop, Node.js uses the libuv library—which, in turn, uses a fixed-sized thread pool that handles some of the non-blocking asynchronous I/O operations.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] A thread pool handles the execution of parallel tasks in Node.js.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] The main thread function call posts tasks to the shared task queue, which threads in the thread pool pull and execute.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Inherently non-blocking system functions such as networking translate to kernel-side non-blocking sockets, while inherently blocking system functions such as file I/O run in a blocking way on their own threads.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] When a thread in the thread pool completes a task, it informs the main thread of this, which in turn, wakes up and executes the registered callback.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] A downside of this single-threaded approach is that Node.js does not allow vertical scaling by increasing the number of CPU cores of the machine it is running on without using an additional module, such as cluster, StrongLoop Process Manager, or pm2.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] However, developers can increase the default number of threads in the libuv thread pool.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] The server operating system (OS) is likely to distribute these threads across multiple cores.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Another problem is that long-lasting computations and other CPU-bound tasks freeze the entire event-loop until completion.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] V8 is the JavaScript execution engine which was initially built for Google Chrome.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] It was then open-sourced by Google in 2008.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Written in C++, V8 compiles JavaScript source code to native machine code at runtime.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] As of 2016, it also includes Ignition, a bytecode interpreter.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] npm is the pre-installed package manager for the Node.js server platform.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] It installs Node.js programs from the npm registry, organizing the installation and management of third-party Node.js programs.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Node.js registers with the operating system so the OS notifies it of asynchronous I/O events such as new connections.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Within the Node.js runtime, events trigger callbacks and each connection is handled as a small heap allocation.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Traditionally, relatively heavyweight OS processes or threads handled each connection.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Node.js uses an event loop for concurrent I/O, instead of processes or threads.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] In contrast to other event-driven servers, Node.js's event loop does not need to be called explicitly.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Instead, callbacks are defined, and the server automatically enters the event loop at the end of the callback definition.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Node.js exits the event loop when there are no further callbacks to be performed.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Node.js supports WebAssembly and as of Node 14 has experimental support of WASI, the WebAssembly System Interface.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Node.js provides a way to create "add-ons" via a C-based API called N-API, which can be used to produce loadable (importable) `.node` modules from source code written in C/C++.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] The modules can be directly loaded into memory and executed from within JS environment as simple CommonJS modules.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] The implementation of the N-API relies on internal C/C++ Node.js and V8 objects requiring users to import (#include) Node.js specific headers into their native source code.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] As the Node.js API is subject to breaking changes at a binary level, modules have to be built and shipped against specific Node.js versions to work properly.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] To address the issue, third parties have introduced open-sourced С/С++ wrappers on top of the API that partially alleviate the problem.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] They simplify interfaces, but as a side effect they may also introduce complexity which maintainers have to deal with.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Even though the core functionality of Node.js resides in a JavaScript built-in library, modules written in C++ can be used to enhance capabilities and to improve performance of applications.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] In order to produce such modules one needs to have an appropriate C++ compiler and necessary headers (the latter are typically shipped with Node.js itself), e.g., gcc, clang or MSVC++.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] The N-API is similar to Java Native Interface.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] OpenHarmony and ArkTS also adopts N-API, with the internal implementation rewritten.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] In 2015, various branches of the greater Node.js community began working under the vendor-neutral Node.js Foundation.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] The Node.js Foundation Technical Steering Committee (TSC) is the technical governing body of the Node.js Foundation.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] The TSC is responsible for the core Node.js repo as well as dependent and adjacent projects.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Generally the TSC delegates the administration of these projects to working groups or committees.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] The LTS group that manages long term supported releases is one such group.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] Other current groups include Website, Streams, Build, Diagnostics, i18n, Evangelism, Docker, Addon API, Benchmarking, Post-mortem, Intl, Documentation, and Testing.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] In August 2017, a third of the TSC members resigned due to a dispute related to the project's code of conduct.
[src:ethers-js/node-js] They resigned after a vote failed to remove a member from the leadership group against whom multiple complaints had been filed.
[src:ethers-js/web3] Academic surveys describe Web3 as combining smart contract platforms, peer-to-peer networks, and cryptographic mechanisms, while noting trade-offs involving scalability, interoperability, and governance.
[src:ethers-js/web3] Critics have expressed concerns over the centralization of wealth to a small group of investors and individuals, or a loss of privacy due to more expansive data collection.
[src:ethers-js/web3] Billionaires like Elon Musk and Jack Dorsey have argued that web3 only serves as a buzzword or marketing term.
[src:ethers-js/web3] Web 1.0 and Web 2.0 refer to eras in the history of the World Wide Web as it evolved through various technologies and formats.
[src:ethers-js/web3] Web 1.0 refers roughly to the period from 1991 to 2004, where most sites consisted of static pages, and the vast majority of users were consumers, not producers of content.
[src:ethers-js/web3] Web 2.0 is based around the idea of "the web as platform" and centers on user-created content uploaded to forums, social media and networking services, blogs, and wikis, among other services.
[src:ethers-js/web3] Web 2.0 is generally considered to have begun around 2004 and continues to the current day.
[src:ethers-js/web3] Web3 is distinct from Tim Berners-Lee's 1999 concept of a Semantic Web, which was also sometimes referred to as Web 3.0.
[src:ethers-js/web3] While the Semantic Web envisioned a web of linked data, web3 in the blockchain context refers to a decentralized internet built upon distributed ledger technologies.
[src:ethers-js/web3] Ethereum co-founder Gavin Wood first popularized the use of the term Web 3.0 in a blockchain context in 2014.
[src:ethers-js/web3] Wood used the term to refer to a "decentralized online ecosystem based on blockchain." "Web3" and "Web 3.0" have been used interchangeably by later writers, leading to confusion between the two concepts.
[src:ethers-js/web3] In popular and industry usage, "Web 3.0" is sometimes used interchangeably with "web3" to refer to blockchain-based proposals rather than the Semantic Web.
[src:ethers-js/web3] The definition of the term has been described by *Bloomberg* journalist Olga Kharif as "hazy", but it revolves around the idea of decentralization and often incorporate blockchain technologies, such as various cryptocurrencies and non-fungible tokens (NFTs).
[src:ethers-js/web3] Kharif has described web3 as an idea that "would build financial assets, in the form of tokens, into the inner workings of almost anything you do online".
[src:ethers-js/web3] Web3 has been proposed as a possible response to the over-centralization of the web in a few Big Tech companies.
[src:ethers-js/web3] Web3 could potentially improve data security, scalability, and privacy.
[src:ethers-js/web3] According Kharif in December 2021, skeptics say the idea "is a long way from proving its use beyond niche applications, many of them tools aimed at crypto traders".
[src:ethers-js/web3] DuPont et al (2024) describe web3 as an umbrella term for NFTs, cryptocurrency, and blockchain which appeals to users who are "not necessarily plugged into the cypher-punk or crypto-anarchist ideals of Bitcoin".
[src:ethers-js/web3] Rohn (2025) describes the term as synonymous with "blockchain economy".
[src:ethers-js/web3] In 2019, *The Conversation* quoted legal scholars discussing concerns over the difficulty of regulating a decentralized web, which they reported might make it more difficult to prevent cybercrime, online harassment, hate speech, and the dissemination of child sexual abuse material.
[src:ethers-js/web3] The concept of Web3 has also been described as a part of a cryptocurrency bubble, and as an extension of harmful and short-lived blockchain-based trends such as NFTs.
[src:ethers-js/web3] The use of cryptocurrencies, NFTs, and blockchains in general also introduce potential harmful environmental effects.
[src:ethers-js/web3] Others have expressed beliefs that web3 and the associated technologies are a pyramid scheme.
[src:ethers-js/web3] Web3 proposals often include decentralized autonomous organizations (DAOs) and decentralized finance (DeFi).
[src:ethers-js/web3] Marlinspike also remarked that the new web resembles the old web.
[src:ethers-js/web3] In 2021, interest in the web3 concept began to increase.
[src:ethers-js/web3] Particular interest spiked toward the end of 2021, largely due to interest from cryptocurrency enthusiasts and investments from high-profile technologists and companies.
[src:ethers-js/web3] Executives from venture capital firm Andreessen Horowitz traveled to Washington, DC, in October 2021 to lobby for the idea as a potential solution to questions about regulation of the web, with which policymakers have been grappling.
[src:ethers-js/web3] *The New York Times* and *Fortune* reported in December 2021 that $27 billion had been invested in blockchain projects due to interest in the Web3 concept.
[src:ethers-js/web3] In late 2021, Reddit, Discord, and other Web 2.0 companies experimented with incorporating web3 technologies into their platforms.
[src:ethers-js/web3] On November 8, 2021, Discord CEO Jason Citron tweeted a screenshot suggesting the platform might be integrating cryptocurrency wallets into their platform.
[src:ethers-js/web3] Two days later, and after heavy user backlash, Discord announced they had no plans to integrate such technologies and that it was an internal-only concept that had been developed in a company-wide hackathon.
[src:ethers-js/web3] It's what parents tell their kids about at night if they want them to grow up to become economists".
[src:ethers-js/web3] That same month, Jack Dorsey, co-founder and former CEO of Twitter, dismissed web3 as a "venture capitalists' plaything".
[src:ethers-js/web3] Dorsey opined that web3 will not democratize the internet, but it will shift power from players like Facebook to venture capital funds like Andreessen Horowitz.
